%===============================================================================
% Abstract
%===============================================================================
\begin{abstract}
Electricity markets rely on operating reserve procurement to manage uncertainty arising from renewable generation. In current practice, reserve requirements are typically determined using simplified uncertainty models that neglect the strong spatial correlations induced by weather. This paper develops a differentiable, learning-based robust optimization framework in which the geometry of ellipsoidal uncertainty sets is learned end-to-end from data. The framework profiles the bilevel problem---minimizing robust dispatch cost subject to coverage constraints---into a single-level objective, and derives the profiled gradient including a quantile-sensitivity correction term. For unknown distributions, a three-way data split (train/tune/calibrate) enables gradient approximation while preserving distribution-free coverage guarantees via split conformal prediction under an exchangeability condition. Two structural regimes are identified: zonal reserve formulations admit closed-form support function gradients, while network-constrained formulations require envelope gradients from dual information; in both regimes, no differentiation through the optimization solver is required. The framework is instantiated on the IEEE~118-bus system, demonstrating how learned correlation structure affects reserve procurement efficiency.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Robust optimization, uncertainty sets, operating reserves, machine learning, conformal prediction, electricity markets.
\end{IEEEkeywords}

%===============================================================================
% I. Introduction
%===============================================================================
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

\IEEEPARstart{E}{lectricity} markets rely on operating reserve procurement and pricing mechanisms to manage uncertainty arising from high penetrations of wind and solar generation. Renewable forecast errors are not only substantial in magnitude but also exhibit strong spatial and temporal correlations due to common weather patterns~\cite{hodge2011wind,pinson2013wind}. When such correlations are ignored, reserve capacity requirements may be inefficiently allocated across the power network, leading to excessive procurement costs, distorted price signals, and reduced overall market efficiency.

Robust optimization provides a principled framework for incorporating uncertainty into power system operations and market clearing~\cite{ben2009robust,bertsimas2011theory}. In security-constrained economic dispatch (SCED) and unit commitment, uncertain parameters---such as net load forecast errors---are assumed to lie within a prescribed \emph{uncertainty set}, and the dispatch solution must remain feasible for all realizations within this set. The geometry of the uncertainty set fundamentally determines the conservatism and cost of the resulting solution~\cite{bertsimas2013adaptive}.

In most practical implementations, uncertainty sets are specified with fixed geometric structure (e.g., polyhedral boxes, spherical balls, or ellipsoids with prescribed covariance), and only their overall size is tuned to meet reliability criteria~\cite{jiang2012robust,zeng2013solving}. While this approach supports tractable market clearing, it limits the ability of reserve and dispatch mechanisms to adapt to spatially and temporally varying correlation patterns observed in renewable forecast errors.

\subsection{Literature Review}

\emph{A) Robust Optimization for Power Systems.}
Robust optimization provides tractable frameworks for decision-making under uncertainty by optimizing against worst-case realizations within a prescribed uncertainty set~\cite{bentalnemirovski1998robust,ben2009robust,bertsimas2004price,bertsimas2011theory}. In power systems, robust methods have been widely adopted for unit commitment and economic dispatch. Bertsimas et al.~\cite{bertsimas2013adaptive} developed adaptive robust optimization for security-constrained unit commitment with polyhedral uncertainty sets. Jiang et al.~\cite{jiang2012robust} proposed two-stage robust unit commitment under wind uncertainty, and Zeng and Zhao~\cite{zeng2013solving} introduced column-and-constraint generation for efficient solution. Lorca et al.~\cite{lorca2016multistage} extended these approaches to multistage settings, while Jabr~\cite{jabr2013adjustable} developed adjustable robust OPF with ellipsoidal sets. These approaches typically assume fixed uncertainty set geometry determined a priori and do not adapt the set shape to data.

\emph{B) Data-Driven and Distributionally Robust Approaches.}
Data-driven approaches construct uncertainty sets from historical observations. Bertsimas et al.~\cite{bertsimas2018datadriven} proposed data-driven robust optimization using hypothesis testing to calibrate set size from data with finite-sample guarantees. Ben-Tal et al.~\cite{ben2004adjustable} introduced adjustable robust solutions with affine recourse policies. Distributionally robust optimization (DRO) provides an alternative by optimizing over ambiguity sets of probability distributions. Mohajerin Esfahani and Kuhn~\cite{esfahani2018data} developed Wasserstein DRO with tractable reformulations, and Gao and Kleywegt~\cite{gao2023distributionally} established sharp finite-sample guarantees for Wasserstein DRO. In power systems, Xiong et al.~\cite{xiong2017distributionally} applied moment-based DRO to unit commitment, and Zhao and Guan~\cite{zhao2016data} developed data-driven stochastic unit commitment. Delage and Ye~\cite{delage2010distributionally} proposed DRO under moment uncertainty with SDP reformulations, while Van Parys et al.~\cite{vanparys2021data} proved asymptotic optimality of Wasserstein DRO among data-driven decision rules. These methods do not directly optimize uncertainty set geometry for downstream decision-making costs. Chance-constrained approaches offer yet another paradigm: Roald and Andersson~\cite{roald2018chance} developed reformulations for AC OPF, and Bienstock et al.~\cite{bienstock2014chance} provided a comprehensive treatment of chance-constrained OPF. Roald et al.~\cite{roald2023power} provide a recent survey of optimization under uncertainty in power systems.

\emph{C) Decision-Focused Learning and Differentiable Optimization.}
Decision-focused learning (DFL) integrates prediction and optimization by training models to minimize downstream decision cost rather than prediction error. Elmachtoub and Grigas~\cite{elmachtoub2022smart} introduced the SPO+ loss for linear programs, and Bertsimas and Kallus~\cite{bertsimas2020predictive} developed prescriptive analytics that maps data directly to decisions. Donti et al.~\cite{donti2017task} proposed task-based end-to-end learning by differentiating through stochastic optimization via KKT conditions. Differentiable optimization layers~\cite{amos2017optnet,agrawal2019differentiable} enable backpropagation through convex programs by implicit differentiation of optimality conditions. Blondel et al.~\cite{blondel2022efficient} developed efficient modular implicit differentiation, and Bolte et al.~\cite{bolte2021nonsmooth} extended this to nonsmooth settings using Clarke's generalized Jacobian. Recent surveys~\cite{mandi2024survey,sadana2025survey,kotary2021end} and generalization analyses~\cite{balghiti2022generalization} have consolidated this rapidly growing field. However, differentiating through optimization solvers can be computationally expensive and numerically challenging; our envelope-based approach avoids this entirely.

\emph{D) Learned Uncertainty Sets.}
A nascent line of work learns uncertainty set parameters end-to-end for robust optimization. Wang et al.~\cite{wang2023learning} proposed learning decision-focused uncertainty sets by minimizing expected cost subject to CVaR coverage constraints, using implicit differentiation through the robust optimization layer. Chenreddy and Delage~\cite{chenreddy2024end} developed end-to-end conditional robust optimization that jointly trains for decision quality and conditional coverage. Goerigk and Kurtz~\cite{goerigk2023data} used neural networks to predict uncertainty set parameters from features, and Ma et al.~\cite{ma2024differentiable} developed differentiable DRO layers for embedding distributionally robust problems in learning pipelines. Dumouchelle et al.~\cite{dumouchelle2024neur2ro} used deep learning to approximate value functions in two-stage robust optimization for computational scalability. Our work differs from these approaches in three key respects: (i) envelope gradients from dual multipliers avoid differentiating through the solver; (ii) conformal calibration provides distribution-free coverage guarantees; and (iii) a profiled gradient structure with an explicit quantile-sensitivity correction accounts for the coupling between shape and size parameters.

\emph{E) Conformal Prediction and Distribution-Free Guarantees.}
Conformal prediction~\cite{vovk2005algorithmic} provides distribution-free uncertainty quantification with finite-sample coverage guarantees under exchangeability. Romano et al.~\cite{romano2019conformalized} developed conformalized quantile regression for adaptive prediction intervals, and Tibshirani et al.~\cite{tibshirani2019conformal} extended conformal methods to handle covariate shift. Angelopoulos and Bates~\cite{angelopoulos2023conformal} provide a comprehensive tutorial. Johnstone and Cox~\cite{johnstone2021conformal} connected conformal prediction to robust optimization by constructing ellipsoidal uncertainty sets with coverage guarantees using Mahalanobis distance. Our work extends this connection by learning the ellipsoid shape end-to-end while preserving conformal coverage through a three-way data split.

\emph{F) Renewable Forecast Uncertainty and Reserves.}
Wind and solar forecast errors exhibit complex spatial and temporal correlation structures that affect reserve requirements. Hodge and Milligan~\cite{hodge2011wind} documented non-Gaussian, heavy-tailed forecast error distributions across multiple timescales. Pinson~\cite{pinson2013wind} reviewed statistical challenges in wind forecasting, highlighting spatial correlations from common weather patterns. Hong and Fan~\cite{hong2016probabilistic} surveyed probabilistic load forecasting. In operating reserves, Papavasiliou et al.~\cite{papavasiliou2011reserve} developed scenario-based stochastic programming for wind reserve requirements, and Morales et al.~\cite{morales2014electricity} provided a comprehensive treatment of integrating renewables in electricity markets. These works motivate the need for correlation-aware uncertainty sets that adapt to varying forecast error patterns---precisely what our learned Cholesky parameterization provides.

\subsection{Contributions}

This paper proposes a learning-based robust optimization framework for operating reserve procurement in which the geometry of uncertainty sets is learned directly from data. The key contributions are:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Profiled Bilevel Formulation with Envelope Gradients.}
A bilevel optimization framework using gauge-based uncertainty sets $\cU_{\btheta,\rho} = \{\bu : s_{\btheta}(\bu) \leq \rho\}$ is profiled into a single-level objective via quantile profiling, and envelope/Clarke gradients of the robust value function are derived from optimal dual multipliers---avoiding differentiation through the optimization solver entirely. The profiled gradient includes a quantile-sensitivity correction term that accounts for the coupling between shape $\btheta$ and size $\rho$ parameters.

\item \textbf{Tuning-Based Gradient Approximation with Distribution-Free Coverage.}
A three-way data split (train/tune/calibrate) with smoothed CDF estimation provides a consistent estimator of the profiled gradient when the distribution is unknown. The calibration step preserves finite-sample coverage guarantees via split conformal prediction under an exchangeability condition.

\item \textbf{Power Systems Application with Two Structural Regimes.}
Instantiation on the IEEE~118-bus system with security-constrained economic dispatch reveals two computational regimes: zonal reserve formulations where all gradients of the support function are closed-form, and network-constrained formulations requiring envelope gradients from SCED dual multipliers. In both regimes, no differentiation through the optimization solver is required. Numerical experiments demonstrate a 4.2\% cost reduction through task-aware learning compared to statistical baselines, with all methods achieving conformal coverage guarantees.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Paper Organization}

The remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section~\ref{sec:formulation} presents the general problem formulation with gauge-based uncertainty sets. Section~\ref{sec:methodology} develops the methodology, including envelope gradients, profiled gradients, and conformal calibration. Section~\ref{sec:case-study} instantiates the framework for the IEEE~118-bus system. Section~\ref{sec:algorithm} presents the complete algorithm. Section~\ref{sec:results} provides numerical results demonstrating the framework's effectiveness. Section~\ref{sec:discussion} discusses practical implications and correlation effects. Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes. Fig.~\ref{fig:roadmap} provides a roadmap of the theoretical development.

