\section{Numerical Results}
\label{sec:results}

We evaluate the proposed framework on the IEEE~118-bus system described in Section~\ref{sec:case-study}.

\subsection{Experimental Setup}

We model uncertainty with $d = 15$ dimensions representing three source types (load, solar, wind) across five geographic regions, with an allocation matrix $A \in \R^{10 \times 15}$ aggregating source-level uncertainty to 10 zonal reserve requirements. Context features $\bxi \in \R^7$ include normalized load, solar, and wind forecasts, plus cyclical time encodings (hour and month).

The dataset comprises 35{,}040 hourly samples (4~years), split chronologically: 60\% training (21{,}024 samples), 20\% tuning (7{,}008), 10\% calibration (3{,}504), and 10\% testing (3{,}504). Training data is used for covariance estimation; tuning data for profiled gradient optimization (Algorithm~\ref{alg:main}); calibration data for conformal radius selection; and the held-out test set for independent coverage verification. The target coverage level is $\tau = 0.95$.

\subsection{Methods}

We compare four approaches for constructing the ellipsoidal uncertainty set $\cU_{\bL,\rho}$, all evaluated under split conformal calibration for fair comparison:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Independent.} $\bL = \diag(\hat\sigma_1, \ldots, \hat\sigma_d)$ where $\hat\sigma_i$ is the marginal standard deviation from training data. This treats each source-region dimension independently, ignoring all cross-dimensional correlations---the standard industry approach.

\item \textbf{Sample Covariance.} $\bL = \text{chol}(\hat\Sigma)$ from the sample covariance $\hat\Sigma = n^{-1}\sum_t \bu_t \bu_t^\top$. This captures all pairwise correlations but is a purely statistical estimator, not optimized for dispatch cost.

\item \textbf{Learned (Static).} A single lower-triangular $\bL \in \R^{d \times d}$ trained via Algorithm~\ref{alg:main} to minimize SCED cost, initialized from the sample covariance. This demonstrates the value of task-aware uncertainty set learning.

\item \textbf{Learned (Contextual).} A neural network $\bL_\phi(\bxi)$ mapping context to Cholesky factors, trained via Algorithm~\ref{alg:main} with per-sample SCED solves. The encoder uses an MLP with hidden dimensions $[128, 64]$, Cholesky construction with $\exp(\cdot)$ diagonal, and trace normalization (Section~\ref{sec:methodology}). Initialized from the Learned (Static) solution.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Results}

