Table~\ref{tab:results} presents the main results. All methods achieve the target 95\% calibration coverage by construction; the held-out test coverage validates the conformal guarantee out of sample.

\textbf{Task-aware learning reduces cost significantly.} The Learned (Static) method reduces dispatch cost by 4.5\% (\$4{,}473/hr) compared to the Independent baseline, while reducing total reserve volume by 39\% (from 1{,}563 to 956~MW). The cost reduction is driven entirely by reserve procurement: reserve cost drops from \$9{,}115/hr to \$4{,}805/hr, while energy dispatch cost decreases modestly from \$90{,}829 to \$90{,}666/hr. This demonstrates that optimizing uncertainty set geometry for downstream dispatch cost---rather than statistical fit---yields substantial efficiency gains. The Sample Covariance method, despite capturing all pairwise correlations, performs comparably to the Independent method (\$100{,}012 vs.\ \$99{,}944), confirming that statistical accuracy of the covariance estimate alone does not guarantee cost efficiency.

\textbf{End-to-end contextual learning.} The Learned (Contextual) method achieves a best training-set cost of \$94{,}404/hr---\$700 below the Static method---demonstrating that the profiled gradient pipeline (Algorithm~\ref{alg:main}) successfully propagates task-relevant information through the neural network encoder. However, this training improvement does not fully transfer to the held-out test set (\$95{,}883 vs.\ \$95{,}471), and test coverage drops to 0.930 (below the 0.95 target), reflecting an overfitting gap. The trace normalization constraint, while ensuring training stability, restricts the network to shape-only adaptation; designing architectures that effectively balance expressiveness with generalization for this class of problems is an important direction for future work.

\textbf{Out-of-sample coverage.} The held-out test set (3{,}504 samples) provides an independent assessment of conformal validity. The Independent and Sample Covariance methods achieve conservative test coverage ($\geq 0.98$), while the Learned (Static) method maintains valid coverage at 0.967 (95\% CI: [0.960, 0.972]). The Learned (Contextual) method falls below the 0.95 target at 0.930 on the test set, suggesting that the learned shapes may overfit to the tuning/calibration distribution---a challenge noted for adaptive conformal methods in non-exchangeable settings.

\textbf{Conformal calibration.} All four methods achieve exactly 95.0\% empirical coverage on the calibration set by construction of the conformal threshold~\eqref{eq:conformal-rho}. The coverage guarantee of Theorem~\ref{thm:conformal} ensures that this level extends to future independent draws from the same distribution; for dependent data, the finite-sample guarantee requires exchangeability (Assumption~\ref{asm:exchange}), which a chronological split may violate (see Remark~3 and Section~\ref{sec:discussion}). To validate out-of-sample coverage, we evaluate on a held-out test set not used in calibration. The comparison across methods is therefore purely on dispatch cost efficiency.

