\subsection{Limitations and Extensions}

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Data Requirements:} The framework requires sufficient historical data to learn correlation patterns. Performance may degrade with limited data or in rapidly changing systems.

\item \textbf{Extreme Events:} Learned models may not generalize well to extreme events outside the training distribution. Robust extensions incorporating worst-case bounds merit investigation.

\item \textbf{Multi-Period Formulations:} Extension to multi-period unit commitment with ramping constraints and inter-temporal coupling is a natural direction.

\item \textbf{AC Power Flow:} The current formulation uses DC power flow approximation. Extension to AC optimal power flow requires additional technical development.

\item \textbf{Dependence and Calibration:} Exact conformal coverage requires exchangeability; extending calibration to dependent time-series settings (e.g., block conformal methods~\cite{barber2023conformal}) requires additional methodological choices.

\item \textbf{Scope of Baselines:} The experiments compare four ellipsoidal uncertainty sets to isolate the effect of learning the covariance structure. Alternative uncertainty set geometries---budgeted polyhedral~\cite{bertsimas2004price}, Wasserstein balls~\cite{esfahani2018data}, or moment-based ambiguity sets~\cite{xiong2017distributionally}---would provide complementary baselines. However, these differ in both geometry and calibration methodology, making it difficult to attribute cost differences to learning vs.\ set geometry. The ellipsoidal comparison controls for geometry and isolates the contribution of task-aware covariance learning. Extension to learned non-ellipsoidal sets is a natural direction.

\item \textbf{Statistical Robustness:} The contextual method (neural network encoder) involves stochastic training sensitive to initialization and random seed. Reporting variance across multiple seeds and sensitivity to hyperparameters ($\varepsilon$, $\tau$, learning rate) would strengthen the empirical evaluation.
\end{enumerate}

