\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

This paper developed a differentiable robust optimization framework for learning correlated uncertainty sets in operating reserve markets. The key contributions are:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Profiled bilevel formulation with envelope gradients:} The bilevel learning problem is profiled into a single-level objective, and envelope/Clarke gradients from optimal dual multipliers provide the profiled gradient---including a quantile-sensitivity correction---without differentiating through the optimization solver.

\item \textbf{Tuning-based gradient approximation with distribution-free coverage:} A three-way data split with smoothed CDF estimation provides a consistent gradient estimator, while conformal calibration preserves finite-sample coverage guarantees under exchangeability.

\item \textbf{Power systems application with two structural regimes:} Instantiation on the IEEE~118-bus SCED reveals zonal formulations with closed-form support function gradients and network-constrained formulations requiring envelope gradients from SCED dual multipliers. In both regimes, no differentiation through the solver is required.
\end{enumerate}

Numerical experiments on the IEEE~118-bus system demonstrate that the task-aware Learned (Static) method reduces dispatch cost by 4.5\% compared to conventional approaches while maintaining out-of-sample coverage above 95\% (test coverage 0.967), validating the practical benefit of task-aware uncertainty set learning. The cost reduction is driven by a 47\% decrease in reserve procurement cost (from \$9{,}115 to \$4{,}805/hr) through correlation-aware shaping of the ellipsoidal set, with total reserve volume reduced by 39\%. End-to-end contextual training via a neural network encoder achieves further cost reduction during training, confirming that the profiled gradient pipeline successfully propagates decision-relevant information through the network; however, generalization to held-out data requires architecture-specific design that we identify as a direction for future work.

Theoretical analysis shows that positive correlation increases system reserve requirements while negative correlation enables hedging, highlighting the importance of accurate correlation modeling for efficient market operations. Future work includes extension to multi-period formulations, integration with real-time balancing markets, neural architecture design for contextual uncertainty set learning, and development of robust extensions for extreme event scenarios.

